For anyone wondering, Agora was a large open and public Forum / Marketplace in ancient Greek cities. Agoraphobia isn't necessarily the fear of leaving the house, but the fear of situations that cause anxiety. The fear of fear, so to say. It's called Agoraphobia because Agora's were often cramped and loud, which can be very anxiety inducing for people with anxiety, so they tended to avoid that. You can still have Agoraphobia in your own 4 walls though.

text:
Ya know I really appreciate you calling out the bizzarro world/painful dystopian stuff, as you are someone who has a lot of actual experience; it's easy as someone who has watched the internet develop for a long time to see how either on-the-nose or genuinely psychotic this kinda dystopian game is (depending on how aware we assume the devs are), but I expect there are some younguns out there who unironically really benefitted from hearing it from you! I think if there is any example to prove that this kind of content-hungry, acting, non-genuine, view-driven, trend-monkey way of being a content creator isn't the way to go, it's that the biggest vtuber on the gosh darn planet is you Guwa; someone who is really herself, who only makes content she has a genuine interest in, and who is a kind and sweet and charming person with no acting required:_gurapat:

Thanks so much for the stream Gwumbus; there really aren't many people I would watch play this game (like I don't think I could watch someone play this who was... actually disturbingly close to the bizzarro world representation of YouTubing; but I trust you to be yourself and call things out and genuinely be the intelligent and aware person you are), and you made it both fun and intriguing. I'm glad you had fun too:_gurapat:Enjoy your cabbage rolls Guwa:_GuYum:

text:
The interesting thing about this game is that the first one wasn't nearly as cringey/bizarro. The first game seemed more... realistic, as far as this type of game can be. It had a "Game Dev Tycoon" vibe in it, where you actually start small and like a regular person - living with your parents, going to school and doing youtube as a sidething -. You had to try and balance those factors and make it big enough so you could move out and be independent, while also paying bills, etc. It still was a cutesy looking simulator, but it had, as well as it could, a tinge of reality. 

This one is fucking insane. It's really a dystopian narrative where everyone is trying to be a Youtuber and every single step is motivated by views, subscriber and trends, where no one is their own person and everyone is just going through the most popular fads.

 So I get the darker factor you were talking about, Goob. Still, if you want to play an actual youtuber simulator, where you do the grind as an almost normal person, would highly recommend the first game. The gameplay too is MUCH more fleshed out, the second one is barebones in comparison.
